Scientific notation

R will convert large numbers to scientific notation. You must command R to not do this to avoid computation errors down the line. This following chunk commands R to avoid scientific notation in output. For help see, Stack overflow: How to prevent scientific notation in R?

options(scipen=999)

Import Data

In this data chunk, I assign the iris data set to a data frame titled data. This will be stored in the Global Environment.

A data set giving the number of publications by doctoral candidates in biochemistry in relation to various predictors, originally from Long (1997).

library(tidyverse) #load additional functions
library(kableExtra)
library(broom)
library(vcdExtra) #load package with data set
data <- PhdPubs #assign data set to data frame titled "data"

"A data frame with 915 observations on the following 6 variables.

articles - number of articles published in the final three years of PhD studies

female - dummy variable for gender, coded 1 for female

married - dummy variable for marital status, coded 1 for married

kid5 - number of young children, age 5 and under

phdprestige - prestige of the PhD department

mentor - number of publications by the mentor in the preceeding three years"

T-tests

pwr::pwr.t.test(n = 457, power = 0.80, sig.level = 0.05)
## 
##      Two-sample t test power calculation 
## 
##               n = 457
##               d = 0.1855337
##       sig.level = 0.05
##           power = 0.8
##     alternative = two.sided
## 
## NOTE: n is number in *each* group

Effect sizes of d = 0.1855337 and above have >80% power, this indicates sufficient power for small effects (d=0.2) and above.

ttest_female <- psych::cohen.d(data ~ female)

  cbind(ttest_female[["cohen.d"]]) %>% round(3)

colnames(ttest_female_table) = c("t","p","lower d", "estimated d", "upper d")

Linear Regression

pwr::pwr.f2.test(u = 5, v=915, sig.level = 0.05, power = 0.8)
## 
##      Multiple regression power calculation 
## 
##               u = 5
##               v = 915
##              f2 = 0.01399133
##       sig.level = 0.05
##           power = 0.8

The power analysis suggests that an f2 value of 0.01399133 is necessary to have 80% power at the 0.05 significance level, with 5 predictors. This means that the model must explain at least 1.4% of the variance to have 80% power (an 80% chance of avoiding a type 2 error false negative).

pwr::pwr.f2.test(u = 5, v=40, sig.level = 0.05, power = 0.8)
## 
##      Multiple regression power calculation 
## 
##               u = 5
##               v = 40
##              f2 = 0.3196103
##       sig.level = 0.05
##           power = 0.8

For a hypothetical comparison, if we were to estimate the same model with only 40 participants, the f2 value would have to equal 0.3196103 to have 80% power.

Comparison to Base R and ggeffects

data$gender <- factor(data$female,
                             levels = c(0,1),
                             labels = c("Male","Female"))

data$married <- factor(data$married,
                             levels = c(0,1),
                             labels = c("Single","Married"))
fit <- lm(articles ~ phdprestige + mentor + kid5 + married + gender, data)

The f2 value calculated from the adjusted r2 value indicated a small effect size for the proportion of explained variance.

QQ-plot to check for normality of residuals.

dat <- resid(fit)
qqnorm(dat, col=adjustcolor("orange", 0.4), pch=19)
qqline(dat)

qqnormsim = function(dat, dim=c(2,2)) {
  par(mfrow=dim)
  qqnorm(dat, col=adjustcolor("orange", 0.4), 
         pch=19, cex=0.7, main="Normal QQ Plot (Data)")
  qqline(dat)
  for (i in 1:(prod(dim) - 1)) {
    simnorm = rnorm(n=length(dat), mean=mean(dat), sd=sd(dat))
    qqnorm(simnorm, col=adjustcolor("orange", 0.4), 
           pch=19, cex=0.7,
           main="Normal QQ Plot (Sim)")
    qqline(simnorm)
  }
  par(mfrow=c(1, 1))
}
qqnormsim(resid(fit))

This qq-plot reflects a heavy right skew, which can potentially threaten the generalizability of these results, since the residuals are non-normal in the upper quantiles. However, in a larger data set (n=915), the impact of the violation of this assumption is less severe than if the data set were small. See here for more information.

car::vif(fit)
## phdprestige      mentor        kid5     married      gender 
##    1.088024    1.091446    1.331998    1.300333    1.124198

Variance inflation factors are all <4, indicating a lack of problematic multicollinearity.

library(ggeffects)
library(jtools)

effect_gender <- ggpredict(fit, terms = c("gender"))

plot(effect_gender, add.data = TRUE) + 
  theme_apa() +
  labs(
    x = "Gender", 
    y = "# of articles published", 
    title = "Marginal effect of gender on # of articles published",
    caption = "estimate = -0.380, p-value = 0.003")

effect_mentor <- ggpredict(fit, terms = c("mentor"))

plot(effect_mentor, add.data = TRUE) + 
  theme_apa() +
  labs(
    x = "# of mentor publications", 
    y = "# of articles published", 
    title = "Marginal effect of mentor publications on # of articles published",
    caption = "estimate = 0.0607, p-value = <0.001")

effect_kid5 <- ggpredict(fit, terms = c("kid5"))

plot(effect_kid5, add.data = TRUE) + 
  theme_apa() +
  labs(
    x = "# of children", 
    y = "# of articles published", 
    title = "Marginal effect of children on # of articles published",
    caption = "estimate = -0.291, p-value = 0.001")
